1
00:00:00,340 --> 00:00:06,620
Here’s my biggest advice to you: don't trade
like everyone else - the real profits in trading

2
00:00:06,620 --> 00:00:12,590
come from being one step ahead, anticipating
the next move before it happens, and not by

3
00:00:12,590 --> 00:00:15,240
reacting using lagging indicators.

4
00:00:15,240 --> 00:00:21,550
90% of trading education is useless in today’s
market, and that’s the reality.

5
00:00:21,550 --> 00:00:29,689
So let me share my discoveries and my process
to seize opportunities before others do.

6
00:00:29,689 --> 00:00:35,290
Money is made in trading by anticipating what
is coming — not by waiting till it happens

7
00:00:35,290 --> 00:00:40,120
and going with the crowd
In trading, being ahead of the curve is the

8
00:00:40,120 --> 00:00:41,450
name of the game.

9
00:00:41,450 --> 00:00:48,010
It's about anticipating the market's moves,
not just reacting to them once they've happened.

10
00:00:48,010 --> 00:00:49,010
Why?

11
00:00:49,010 --> 00:00:53,350
Because by the time the rest of the crowd
catches up, it's often too late to make the

12
00:00:53,350 --> 00:00:55,320
most of the situation.

13
00:00:55,320 --> 00:01:01,090
If you anticipate the market's 'next wave'
in advance, you can 'ride' it profitably.

14
00:01:01,090 --> 00:01:06,950
But if you just stand there and let it hit
you, you will find yourself knocked over.

15
00:01:06,950 --> 00:01:13,000
Consider a breakout in the market, where prices
suddenly move outside a defined range.

16
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:17,820
This could be the start of a new trend or
a market manipulation practice.

17
00:01:17,820 --> 00:01:23,790
If you've done your analysis and predicted
the breakout, you can buy in early and potentially

18
00:01:23,790 --> 00:01:27,049
profit as the trend takes off.

19
00:01:27,049 --> 00:01:33,329
But if you're just going along with the crowd,
using lagging and outdated tools, you'll often

20
00:01:33,329 --> 00:01:39,600
end up buying in too late, after the breakout
has already happened and the price has shot

21
00:01:39,600 --> 00:01:40,600
up.

22
00:01:40,600 --> 00:01:46,860
A similar principle applies to pullbacks – short-term
reversals in an uptrend or downtrends.

23
00:01:46,860 --> 00:01:51,860
If you've done your homework and expect a
pullback, you can plan your trades to take

24
00:01:51,860 --> 00:01:54,900
advantage of this temporary dip.

25
00:01:54,900 --> 00:01:58,160
Buying at a discount or selling at a premium.

26
00:01:58,160 --> 00:02:05,710
The key to making money in trading is anticipation,
not just blindly following some delayed signals,

27
00:02:05,710 --> 00:02:07,289
like most of the crowd.

28
00:02:07,289 --> 00:02:14,510
Let me repeat: trading is about anticipating
the market's next move, not reacting to what's

29
00:02:14,510 --> 00:02:16,140
already happened.

30
00:02:16,140 --> 00:02:19,670
It's a proactive, not a reactive approach.

31
00:02:19,670 --> 00:02:24,070
If your trading strategy is 100% reactive,
you have a big problem.

32
00:02:24,070 --> 00:02:26,350
Big moves start from dull, flat markets, not
from active ones.

33
00:02:26,350 --> 00:02:30,670
Big moves start from flat markets, not from
active ones.

34
00:02:30,670 --> 00:02:35,819
When the market is ‘going nowhere’, pay
close attention, and wait for a strong move

35
00:02:35,819 --> 00:02:38,780
that is certain to eventually happen.

36
00:02:38,780 --> 00:02:43,390
As I said before, the essence of trading is
anticipation.

37
00:02:43,390 --> 00:02:47,990
Successful trading involves predicting the
future direction of the market based on its

38
00:02:47,990 --> 00:02:49,790
current conditions.

39
00:02:49,790 --> 00:02:56,520
And a common mistake is to dismiss a dull
market as unprofitable and ignore it.

40
00:02:56,520 --> 00:03:03,799
Big moves in the market often originate from
these periods, not from times of high activity.

41
00:03:03,799 --> 00:03:09,580
During these seemingly uneventful periods
the market is setting the stage for significant

42
00:03:09,580 --> 00:03:10,580
moves.

43
00:03:10,580 --> 00:03:15,860
So, when you feel the market is stagnant or
flat, don't let your guard down.

44
00:03:15,860 --> 00:03:22,349
Instead, sharpen your focus and wait for the
eventual substantial move that could follow.

45
00:03:22,349 --> 00:03:28,269
These are the accumulation and distribution
periods, during which smart money are planning

46
00:03:28,269 --> 00:03:32,720
their next moves
During these periods you have the chance to

47
00:03:32,720 --> 00:03:38,420
position yourself for the wave that's about
to come.

48
00:03:38,420 --> 00:03:43,531
Successful trading relies on certain conditions,
and the most important factor is the market

49
00:03:43,531 --> 00:03:47,819
volatility - the extent of price swings.

50
00:03:47,819 --> 00:03:54,319
Every day prices fluctuate constantly, rising
and falling in response to various factors.

51
00:03:54,319 --> 00:03:58,739
As a trader, your goal is to profit from these
price changes.

52
00:03:58,739 --> 00:04:04,140
But when the market is 'quiet,' and prices
aren't moving much, there's not much opportunity

53
00:04:04,140 --> 00:04:05,519
to make money.

54
00:04:05,519 --> 00:04:10,010
I’m not talking about ranges, or accumulation
or distribution periods.

55
00:04:10,010 --> 00:04:15,760
I’m talking about the distance price travels
during a day.

56
00:04:15,760 --> 00:04:20,820
Trading during quiet, or low-volatility periods
is a common mistake.

57
00:04:20,820 --> 00:04:27,440
If the price of a market is barely moving,
there's little chance to make a profit.

58
00:04:27,440 --> 00:04:30,760
Let's say it costs you 5 dollars to trade.

59
00:04:30,760 --> 00:04:35,889
This represents the commissions or fees you
need to pay for each trade you make.

60
00:04:35,889 --> 00:04:41,729
If the stock you trade only moves around 5
to 10 dollars, you'll need to catch almost

61
00:04:41,729 --> 00:04:46,070
every single swing perfectly just to break
even.

62
00:04:46,070 --> 00:04:52,190
If you factor in the occasional loss, it becomes
clear why trading in a quiet market can be

63
00:04:52,190 --> 00:04:54,060
a losing game.

64
00:04:54,060 --> 00:04:59,630
The solution is to look for markets with sufficient
volatility - ones where prices are moving

65
00:04:59,630 --> 00:05:02,860
enough to offer potential for profit.

66
00:05:02,860 --> 00:05:09,310
Use the average true range or the average
daily range to determine the best markets

67
00:05:09,310 --> 00:05:11,009
to be in.

68
00:05:11,009 --> 00:05:16,169
With these tools, you ensure that the markets
you're trading have enough room to move.

69
00:05:16,169 --> 00:05:20,949
Trading Cannot Be Reduced to Simple Rules
Trading is like playing a video game, where

70
00:05:20,949 --> 00:05:24,410
each level brings new scenarios and challenges.

71
00:05:24,410 --> 00:05:30,860
And here's the catch: No two scenarios in
this game ever repeat exactly.

72
00:05:30,860 --> 00:05:34,919
Every new scene or challenge is different
from the last.

73
00:05:34,919 --> 00:05:36,860
Financial markets are the same.

74
00:05:36,860 --> 00:05:42,590
Each day in the market is a new day with different
situations and it's impossible to find two

75
00:05:42,590 --> 00:05:46,650
situations that are 100% identical.

76
00:05:46,650 --> 00:05:52,000
The market is always changing, evolving with
new subtleties and nuances.

77
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:58,300
Now, imagine you try to use the same strategy
for every level in your game - it's not going

78
00:05:58,300 --> 00:05:59,610
to work.

79
00:05:59,610 --> 00:06:01,440
Same goes for trading.

80
00:06:01,440 --> 00:06:07,670
If you create a simple set of rules based
on EURUSD, it might not work on other markets.

81
00:06:07,670 --> 00:06:11,810
It’s so obvious, but many traders don’t
realize this.

82
00:06:11,810 --> 00:06:17,610
They take a strategy designed for certain
market conditions, and apply it in different

83
00:06:17,610 --> 00:06:19,310
environment.

84
00:06:19,310 --> 00:06:20,830
Most likely, it won’t work!

85
00:06:20,830 --> 00:06:25,680
Your edge should be based on your own observations
If you're a new trader, instead of rushing

86
00:06:25,680 --> 00:06:29,569
into the game, you need to prioritize observation.

87
00:06:29,569 --> 00:06:35,250
If you focus on building a strategy before
observing the market behavior, you’re doing

88
00:06:35,250 --> 00:06:36,250
it wrong.

89
00:06:36,250 --> 00:06:43,630
You need to base your edge on careful observation
and understanding of market patterns and behaviors.

90
00:06:43,630 --> 00:06:50,600
This is very important: if your trading strategy
isn't rooted in your observations and understanding,

91
00:06:50,600 --> 00:06:56,780
you'll lack the confidence to stick to your
plan, especially when the market gets rough.

92
00:06:56,780 --> 00:07:03,010
Trading requires a unique approach tailored
to your observations and understanding.

93
00:07:03,010 --> 00:07:04,660
My advice?

94
00:07:04,660 --> 00:07:07,030
Spend a full week observing price action.

95
00:07:07,030 --> 00:07:09,250
Don’t take any trades.

96
00:07:09,250 --> 00:07:13,500
Just open a chart, and look at the action
in real time.

97
00:07:13,500 --> 00:07:18,160
Reflect on the market patterns or behaviors
that caught your attention.

98
00:07:18,160 --> 00:07:22,660
How does the market behave before an upward
or downward trend?

99
00:07:22,660 --> 00:07:26,780
What's the most reliable market behavior you've
observed?

100
00:07:26,780 --> 00:07:33,069
These high-quality observations are the key
to identifying your unique edge.

101
00:07:33,069 --> 00:07:37,889
They will guide you in creating a good strategy
that aligns with the market's rhythm.

102
00:07:37,889 --> 00:07:40,169
Always try to take a free position

103
00:07:40,169 --> 00:07:45,460
Wyckoff, the famous trader, was a firm believer
in taking free positions.

104
00:07:45,460 --> 00:07:48,370
And this is something I’ve integrated in
my trading plan.

105
00:07:48,370 --> 00:07:54,720
“Taking a Free Position” is a strategic
method to safeguard and secure your gains.

106
00:07:54,720 --> 00:07:56,220
It’s simple.

107
00:07:56,220 --> 00:07:59,750
Let's say you've placed a trade and it's going
in your favor.

108
00:07:59,750 --> 00:08:04,539
To protect your profits, you move your stop
loss, following the price.

109
00:08:04,539 --> 00:08:09,379
This way, even if the price suddenly drops,
you won't lose any money.

110
00:08:09,379 --> 00:08:14,460
It's like setting a safety net that moves
up with the price.

111
00:08:14,460 --> 00:08:20,470
Doing this helps you squeeze out every bit
of profit from the trade.

112
00:08:20,470 --> 00:08:25,919
And the great thing is, as long as you don't
decide to close the trade yourself, there's

113
00:08:25,919 --> 00:08:28,979
always a chance for more profit.

114
00:08:28,979 --> 00:08:33,750
If you get frustrated when you close a trade
for a profit, and you see the price going

115
00:08:33,750 --> 00:08:37,240
even higher, this is the answer.

116
00:08:37,240 --> 00:08:43,800
Instead of setting a fixed target and calling
it a day once he hit that, you follow the

117
00:08:43,800 --> 00:08:49,880
trade and adjust the stop loss according to
the price swings, going for the maximum possible

118
00:08:49,880 --> 00:08:53,130
profit each time.

119
00:08:53,130 --> 00:08:58,120
Consistently adjusting your stop-loss, following
the market's rise or fall, leaves room for

120
00:08:58,120 --> 00:09:05,850
additional profit, whereas prematurely closing
your trade seals off any such potential opportunities.

121
00:09:05,850 --> 00:09:11,339
The Holy Grail of Trading (If There Was One)
Too many traders spend excessive time constantly

122
00:09:11,339 --> 00:09:17,700
tweaking their setups, playing around with
their charts, and making unnecessary modifications

123
00:09:17,700 --> 00:09:19,160
every other day.

124
00:09:19,160 --> 00:09:25,450
This practice isn't just time-consuming but
can also destroy your trading strategy.

125
00:09:25,450 --> 00:09:30,880
Imagine you've identified your edge - your
unique understanding of market behavior that

126
00:09:30,880 --> 00:09:32,970
gives you an advantage.

127
00:09:32,970 --> 00:09:38,190
Your next step is to set up your charts in
a way that allows you to trade according to

128
00:09:38,190 --> 00:09:39,260
your plan.

129
00:09:39,260 --> 00:09:45,910
But here's the catch: make a commitment to
yourself to resist making any changes to it

130
00:09:45,910 --> 00:09:48,220
for at least a month.

131
00:09:48,220 --> 00:09:53,600
If you're constantly altering your charts
and setups, you won't be able to distinguish

132
00:09:53,600 --> 00:09:58,810
what strategies are successful and which ones
you should avoid.

133
00:09:58,810 --> 00:10:05,680
Consistency, in essence, is the closest thing
to a Holy Grail in trading.

134
00:10:05,680 --> 00:10:09,800
Make a decision and have the discipline to
stick to it.

135
00:10:09,800 --> 00:10:15,630
If your trading strategy varies every day,
how can you possibly evaluate what's working

136
00:10:15,630 --> 00:10:16,740
and what's not?

137
00:10:16,740 --> 00:10:23,320
It's ironic that many traders demand consistency
from the market but fail to apply the same

138
00:10:23,320 --> 00:10:27,620
principle to their trading behavior.

139
00:10:27,620 --> 00:10:30,800
The Four Foundations of Successful Trading
Jesse Livermore, the famous trader, said that

140
00:10:30,800 --> 00:10:40,230
a consistent trader needs to master 4 skills:
observation, experience, memory, and mathematics.

141
00:10:40,230 --> 00:10:51,470
You need good observation skills 
to

142
00:10:51,470 --> 00:10:52,930
Experience comes with time.

143
00:10:52,930 --> 00:10:59,370
It's not just about winning or losing trades,
but understanding what worked and what didn't.

144
00:10:59,370 --> 00:11:04,200
You get better as you understand the market
mechanics better.

145
00:11:04,200 --> 00:11:06,339
Memory is your personal database.

146
00:11:06,339 --> 00:11:12,390
It involves remembering past trades, market
patterns, and changes.

147
00:11:12,390 --> 00:11:15,260
Mathematics is the analytical part.

148
00:11:15,260 --> 00:11:21,190
It involves crunching numbers, analyzing charts,
and predicting market trends.

149
00:11:21,190 --> 00:11:28,630
These 4 skills work together, will allow you
to evaluate the market conditions accurately.

150
00:11:28,630 --> 00:11:34,290
Missing any of these elements will leave you
ineffective and likely unsuccessful.

151
00:11:34,290 --> 00:11:38,250
That’s the reality!

152
00:11:38,250 --> 00:11:44,160
Should you trade with a system (a set of 100%
objectively defined rules) or with discretion

153
00:11:44,160 --> 00:11:49,420
(using your judgment)
Trading can seem like a binary choice between

154
00:11:49,420 --> 00:11:55,790
following a system (a set of objective rules)
or relying on discretion (leveraging your

155
00:11:55,790 --> 00:11:56,790
judgment).

156
00:11:56,790 --> 00:12:02,420
I try to use both approaches, I’m what they
call a 'hybrid trader.'

157
00:12:02,420 --> 00:12:10,240
You can have a set of rules in place (‘trading
guidelines’), without them being 100% objective.

158
00:12:10,240 --> 00:12:14,029
There is room for rules as well as judgment.

159
00:12:14,029 --> 00:12:21,970
However, if you're new to trading, your approach
should lean more towards systematic trading.

160
00:12:21,970 --> 00:12:26,730
Systematic trading is more beneficial for
a beginner, because trading with objective

161
00:12:26,730 --> 00:12:34,210
rules creates a uniform trading system, thus
promoting a coherent approach to the markets.

162
00:12:34,210 --> 00:12:41,110
When trading using discretion, the chances
of committing mistakes are significantly higher,

163
00:12:41,110 --> 00:12:42,910
particularly as a beginner.

164
00:12:42,910 --> 00:12:48,260
So, if you're just starting, it's better to
be wholly systematic.

165
00:12:48,260 --> 00:12:55,180
As you gain more experience and a deeper understanding
of the market dynamics, you can begin to incorporate

166
00:12:55,180 --> 00:13:00,050
elements of discretionary judgement into your
trading strategy.

167
00:13:00,050 --> 00:13:04,420
It's all about finding the balance that suits
your style and risk tolerance.

168
00:13:04,420 --> 00:13:09,079
Start with Minimum Size
The art of trading is similar to mastering

169
00:13:09,079 --> 00:13:11,880
a new skill or sport.

170
00:13:11,880 --> 00:13:17,260
Just as a beginner doesn't start playing a
sport in the major leagues, a new trader doesn't

171
00:13:17,260 --> 00:13:21,710
start by investing huge sums of money right
off the bat.

172
00:13:21,710 --> 00:13:25,020
It’s a common mistake new traders make.

173
00:13:25,020 --> 00:13:31,210
The safest and most effective way to learn
is to start slow and small, and then gradually

174
00:13:31,210 --> 00:13:36,010
work your way up as your confidence and competence
grow.

175
00:13:36,010 --> 00:13:41,180
If you've done your homework and absorbed
all the information you could find about trading

176
00:13:41,180 --> 00:13:47,200
- the techniques, strategies, tips and tricks
- then it's time to apply that knowledge.

177
00:13:47,200 --> 00:13:53,740
But it's best to start trading in small quantities,
with a few shares or mini lots.

178
00:13:53,740 --> 00:13:59,160
This allows you to gain real trading experience
without risking a significant amount of your

179
00:13:59,160 --> 00:14:00,160
capital.

180
00:14:00,160 --> 00:14:05,440
Now, this approach may not seem exciting to
some, especially those who love the thrill

181
00:14:05,440 --> 00:14:09,690
of gambling and want to make a big splash
right away.

182
00:14:09,690 --> 00:14:12,620
But the goal here is not to gamble.

183
00:14:12,620 --> 00:14:18,529
It's not about making a lot of money quickly;
it's about learning to make money consistently

184
00:14:18,529 --> 00:14:20,450
over the long term.

185
00:14:20,450 --> 00:14:27,220
So start small, gain experience, and gradually
increase the size of your trades as you become

186
00:14:27,220 --> 00:14:29,260
more skilled and confident.

187
00:14:29,260 --> 00:14:34,220
The Truth about Market Edges
So, the market you trade today is not the

188
00:14:34,220 --> 00:14:38,370
market you traded yesterday and is not the
market you will trade tomorrow.

189
00:14:38,370 --> 00:14:43,740
That’s because the market participants change,
as do their trading strategies

190
00:14:43,740 --> 00:14:49,810
So, if you're expecting a continued winning
streak, brace yourself for disappointment.

191
00:14:49,810 --> 00:14:51,440
The market doesn't work that way.

192
00:14:51,440 --> 00:14:57,990
Even if you find an edge, that edge could
and in fact will disappear over time.

193
00:14:57,990 --> 00:15:04,340
In my trading journey, I've found several
edges, all of which eventually faded.

194
00:15:04,340 --> 00:15:09,350
You need to understand this: you cannot just
come up with a profitable system and then

195
00:15:09,350 --> 00:15:14,040
use it for the next twenty years to become
insanely rich.

196
00:15:14,040 --> 00:15:20,209
If your method has any edge, that edge will
change and decrease over time.

197
00:15:20,209 --> 00:15:25,240
That’s what is meant when it is said that
‘there is no Holy Grail’ in trading.

198
00:15:25,240 --> 00:15:27,829
I’m not trying to discourage you.

199
00:15:27,829 --> 00:15:34,149
The point is, in order to succeed, you must
keep your trading strategies in sync with

200
00:15:34,149 --> 00:15:36,490
the evolving markets.

201
00:15:36,490 --> 00:15:42,690
If your successful strategy starts to lose
its power, you must reengineer it and adjust

202
00:15:42,690 --> 00:15:44,529
it to new conditions.

203
00:15:44,529 --> 00:15:46,860
What’s my personal edge?

204
00:15:46,860 --> 00:15:52,279
It involves supply and demand and volume spread
analysis concepts.

205
00:15:52,279 --> 00:15:58,009
If you want to know more about it, check out
this trading course, where I explain in detail

206
00:15:58,009 --> 00:16:00,250
exactly how I trade.

207
00:16:00,250 --> 00:16:05,149
And check out our academy program, if you
want to further level up your trading.

208
00:16:05,149 --> 00:16:06,339
Until next time!

